# JSON manifests — explicit edge cache via s-maxage + CDN-Cache-Control.
# 2026-05-07: R8_LOAD_TEST_AUDIT detected cf-cache-status: DYNAMIC on every
# /server.json, /mcp-server.json, /docs/openapi/v1.json, /openapi.agent.json
# request → 100% of crawler/MCP-discovery traffic was hitting Fly origin and
# bottlenecking the single Tokyo machine (HN spike OOM risk). Cloudflare Pages
# does not cache application/json by default extension match; only an explicit
# s-maxage directive (or CDN-Cache-Control) makes the edge participate.
# max-age=300 keeps browsers re-validating quickly so version bumps reach
# clients within 5 min; s-maxage=600 + CDN-Cache-Control=600 hands the edge
# a 10-min TTL that absorbs HN/X spike bursts. Verified live with
# `curl -sI https://jpcite.com/server.json | grep cf-cache-status` flipping
# from DYNAMIC → MISS → HIT after redeploy.
# NOTE on Cross-Origin-Resource-Policy: the global /* rule above pins CORP to
# `same-site`, which would block legitimate cross-origin SDK fetches of these
# manifests. Each JSON manifest route below explicitly sets
# `Cross-Origin-Resource-Policy: cross-origin` to override the global default
# so MCP-discovery clients on any origin can still fetch the manifest. The
# CORS allowlist remains `*` (intentional: these manifests are non-sensitive
# discovery surfaces).
/openapi/*.json
  Content-Type: application/json; charset=utf-8
  Cache-Control: public, max-age=300, s-maxage=600
  CDN-Cache-Control: public, max-age=600
  Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *
  Cross-Origin-Resource-Policy: cross-origin

/v1/openapi*.json
  Content-Type: application/json; charset=utf-8
  Cache-Control: public, max-age=300, s-maxage=600
  CDN-Cache-Control: public, max-age=600
  Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *
  Cross-Origin-Resource-Policy: cross-origin

